SOLID Principles — SRP & OCP (Session Notes)

🐦 The Problem: Design a Bird
Requirement: Design a Bird class with attributes and methods.
Version 0 — Initial Design:
class Bird with:

Attributes: weight, colour, type
Methods: eat(), makeSound(), fly()

makeSound() used a chain of if-else blocks to handle different bird types (sparrow → "chi chi", pigeon → "gutargoon", crow → "kaw kaw").

❌ Problems with Version 0
1. Readability
With a large number of bird types, the makeSound() method becomes bloated with countless else-if blocks, making it hard to read and maintain.
2. Testability
Testing frameworks like JUnit require a separate test function per bird type. For 500 birds, you'd need 500 test functions just for makeSound(), making it practically untestable at scale.
3. Parallel Development
With 5 developers each handling 100 birds on a shared Bird class file, git merge conflicts become inevitable. Every developer pulls, modifies the same file, and pushes — leading to constant conflicts that require manual resolution. Version 0 makes parallel development a mess.
4. SRP Violation
makeSound() had two reasons to change:

A new bird type is added (new else-if block needed)
A bird's sound gets corrected (logic inside a specific else-if changes)

Having two reasons to change = two responsibilities = SRP violation.

✅ Version 1 — Partial Fix (SRP Improvement)
void makeSound() {
    if (type == "sparrow") makeSparrowSound();
    if (type == "pigeon") makePigeonSound();
}

Delegates sound logic to separate functions.
Now makeSound() has only one reason to change — if a new bird is added.
Better SRP, but still modifies old code when adding new birds → violates OCP.


📌 SRP — Single Responsibility Principle

Every code unit (method, class, package) should have a single, cleanly defined responsibility and only one reason to change.

SRP Code Smells:

Methods with lots of else-if blocks
Monster methods — one huge function doing everything (common among beginners)
Folders like shared/common/utilities — dumping grounds that become cluttered over time if not properly managed


📌 OCP — Open/Closed Principle

A class should be closed for modification but open for extension.

Why? To avoid regression errors — where old, working functionality breaks when new features are added. If old code is never touched, regression cannot happen.
✅ Version 2 — OCP + SRP Fix
abstract class Bird {
    weight, colour, type
    eat()
    fly()
    makeSound()
}

class Sparrow extends Bird { eat(), fly(), makeSound() }
class Pigeon extends Bird  { eat(), fly(), makeSound() }

Every new bird gets its own class, extending Bird.
Old code is never touched → no regression risk.
Each class has a single responsibility → SRP satisfied.
✅ Best solution so far.


📌 LSP — Liskov Substitution Principle (Intro)


Don't surprise the client
Don't advertise something you can't do
Abstractions must stay in sync with implementations


Real-world example — UberEats & Paytm bug:

A new developer added a cancelled status to the Paytm payment enum.
checkout() only checked if status != failure, so cancelled orders still got processed.
Users got free food — classic LSP violation where a surprising API change broke dependent systems.


